0000</color></font><width>200</width><height>70</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>0</thickness><color>transparent</color></border><background><color>transparent</color></background></styles></heading><paragraph id="T_2" locked="0"><name>New Text 2</name><content>Ruby is a dynamic programming language with a complex but expressive grammar and a core class library with a rich and powerful API.

Ruby is a pure object-oriented language. Every value is an object, even simple numeric literals and the values true, false and nil.

Ruby syntax is expression-oriented.

Ruby's string are mutable. The []= operator allows you to alter the characters of a string or to insert, delete and replace substrings. The &lt;&lt; operator allows you to append to a string.

The video below explains some concepts about the Ruby language.</content><styles><font><size>14</size><style>normal</style><color>#000000</color></font><width>720</width><height>364</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>0</thickness><color>transparent</color></border><background><color>transparent</color></background></styles></paragraph><button id="T_3" locked="0" type="continue"><name>New Text 3</name><content>Continue</content><styles><font><size>24</size><style>bold</style><color>#FFFFFF</color></font><width>158</width><height>52</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>2</thickness><color>#000000</color></border><background><color>#113E87</color></background></styles></button><heading id="T_4" locked="0"><name>New Text 4</name><content>Arrays</content><styles><font><size>28</size><style>bold</style><color>#000000</color></font><width>200</width><height>70</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>0</thickness><color>transparent</color></border><background><color>transparent</color></background></styles></heading><heading id="T_5" locked="0"><name>New Text 5</name><content>Hashes</content><styles><font><size>28</size><style>bold</style><color>#000000</color></font><width>200</width><height>70</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>0</thickness><color>transparent</color></border><background><color>transparent</color></background></styles></heading><button id="T_6" locked="0" type="skip"><name>New Text 6</name><content>Skip</content><styles><font><size>24</size><style>bold</style><color>#FFFFFF</color></font><width>158</width><height>52</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>2</thickness><color>#000000</color></border><background><color>#113E87</color></background></styles></button><paragraph id="T_7" locked="0"><name>New Text 7</name><content>An array is a sequence of values that allows values to be accessed by their position, or index, in the sequence.

Ruby's arrays are untyped and mutable.

Examples:
[1,2,3] #An array that holds three Fixnum objects
[-10...0, 0..10] #An array of two ranges; trailing commas are allowed
[[1,2],[3,4],[5]] #An array of nested arrays
[x+y, x-y, x*y] #Array elements can be arbitrary expressions
[] #The empty array has size 0</content><styles><font><size>14</size><style>normal</style><color>#000000</color></font><width>407.5</width><height>315</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>0</thickness><color>transparent</color></border><background><color>transparent</color></background></styles></paragraph><paragraph id="T_8" locked="0"><name>New Text 8</name><content>A Hash is a data structure that maintains a set of objects known as keys, and associates a value with each key.

Hashes are also known as maps.

Examples:
numbers = Hash.new # Create a new, empty, hash object
numbers["one"] = 1 # Map the String "one" to the Fixnum 1
numbers["two"] = 2 # Not that we are using array notation here
sum = numbers["one"] + numbers["two"] # Retrieve values like this</content><styles><font><size>14</size><style>normal</style><color>#000000</color></font><width>413.75</width><height>380</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>0</thickness><color>transparent</color></border><background><color>transparent</color></background></styles></paragraph><button id="T_9" locked="0" type="continue"><name>New Text 9</name><content>Continue</content><styles><font><size>24</size><style>bold</style><color>#FFFFFF</color></font><width>158</width><height>52</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>2</thickness><color>#000000</color></border><background><color>#113E87</color></background></styles></button><paragraph id="T_10" locked="0"><name>New Text 10</name><content>my_a = [1,2,3]</content><styles><font><size>32</size><style>normal</style><color>#000000</color></font><width>250</width><height>63.75</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>0</thickness><color>transparent</color></border><background><color>transparent</color></background></styles></paragraph><heading id="T_11" locked="0"><name>New Text 11</name><content>Try some Arrays and Hashes</content><styles><font><size>28</size><style>bold</style><color>#000000</color></font><width>477.5</width><height>61.25</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>0</thickness><color>transparent</color></border><background><color>transparent</color></background></styles></heading><paragraph id="T_12" locked="0"><name>New Text 12</name><content>books =&gt; {
