These blocks are delimited by keywords or punctuation, for example, the curly bracket '}' or the keyword 'end'.

There are two kinds of blocks in Ruby programs, "block" and "body".

One example of a block is: 3.times { print "Ruby! " }

A body is just the list of statements that comprise the body of a class definition, a method definition, a while loop, or whatever.

Bodies are never delimited with curly bracers in Ruby.

On the right side there's an schematic example of bodies. Don't mind the complexity it's just to give an example :).</content><styles><font><size>14</size><style>normal</style><color>#000000</color></font><width>377</width><height>502</height><rotation>0</rotation><border><thickness>0</thickness><color>transparent</color></border><background><color>transparent</color></background></styles></paragraph><paragraph id="T_16" locked="0"><name>New Text 16</name><content>module Stats                                 # A Module
